fix(FieldAccessTest): adapt FieldAccessTest to oracle jdk 11/jdt changes (#2789) Related to adding a travis build with jdk 11 See #2782 

`CtFieldWrite.getTarget()` on `array.length` used to return a `CtVariableWrite` for some reasons... But with jdk 11 now returns  a `CtVariableRead`...

`FieldAccessTest#testFieldAccessOnUnknownType()` has been changed to handle both... by expecting a `CtVariableAccess`.

This (combined with #2787) fixes tests for jdk 11 as can be seen here ( https://travis-ci.org/INRIA/spoon/jobs/460289160 ).
Wether this is satisfaying or not, is up to debate. WDYT?

feat: Use Apache Common Compressor API to [de]compress serialized models (#2165) Since #2094 and #2103 we can [de]serialize the model (CtFactory) with standard java serialization in a file, or a gzip file to save space. Choice was made to write things so that we can add new compression types easily. 

In this PR, I propose to use Apache Common Compressor API (+other files needed for some compression types such as LZMA).

Main changes in src/main/java/spoon/support/SerializationModelStreamer.java and its junit test case src/test/java/spoon/test/serializable/ModelStreamerTest.java and of course pom.xml.

I don't know what you think about adding a new lib, but this lib allows very easily (i) to test what compressor is used for an inputstream (except 7zip btw), (ii) to decompress, (iii) to compress.

Looking forward discussing it with you guyz :)
Cheers,
Mehdi

fix(position): Invalid end column (#2159) Hi! I've found out that `getEndColumn()` from `CompoundSourcePositionImpl` works incorrectly.
Here are 2 screenshots to illustrate the problem.    
Now:
![not_ok](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/32983915/42217181-e2d869a0-7ecc-11e8-8914-7855230e52d8.png)
Expected:
![ok](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/32983915/42217212-fae6828e-7ecc-11e8-8875-63645851cfa6.png)

The problem is that only `getEndLine()` has been overriden, but not `getEndColumn()`.
So this PR contains fix and additional test.

refactor: add transient modifiers in StandardEnvironment.java (#2059) This repair is made by an automatic sonarqube-repair tool that I'm currently writing. It repairs the [bug](https://rules.sonarsource.com/java/type/Bug/RSPEC-1948) by adding transient modifier to all non-serializable fields in this class.

The diff is ugly because sniper mode of spoon is not yet available. But the only changes are that transient modifier is added to 9 fields.

The [repair tool](https://github.com/kth-tcs/sonarqube-repair) uses spoon itself and currently has fixes for 5 bugs : [sonar-bugs](https://sonarqube.ow2.org/project/issues?id=fr.inria.gforge.spoon%3Aspoon-core&resolved=false&rules=squid%3AS1854%2Csquid%3AS1948%2Csquid%3AS2055%2Csquid%3AS2259&types=BUG) and another one to close resources properly.

I would like to get feedback from the community. My goal is to make more pull requests in future and remove all the [sonarqube bugs](https://sonarqube.ow2.org/project/issues?id=fr.inria.gforge.spoon%3Aspoon-core&resolved=false&types=BUG) from spoon.

Fix(noclasspath): access lookup in lambda expressions in noclasspath mode. Closes #813

Until now, a token within a lambda (noclasspath mode) is always
considered a variable access (in particular a CtLocalVariable), though,
it also could refer to a type---a class for instance. This commit adds
two features:

1) An improved variable lookup method which ensures that a found
variable is visible in current context. Furthermore, the amount of
cloned code has been reduced.

2) Check if a given token (SingleNameReference) is a variable or type
access and create an appropriate AST node instead of always creating
a local variable reference.

* fixed a comment.

* Properly handle parameter accesses in anonymous classes.

* Fixed source position calculation in `createTypeAccessNoClasspath`

Fixes #813 as well.

* Added first lines to search for statically imported variables and variables declared in super classes/interfaces.

* Added a simple test checking a type access in a lambda.

* Create concrete variable access.

* Added a test showing that a field access is properly handled in lambdas.

* Find variables declared in super classes/fields.

* Added several Tests for fields accesses.

* Improved variable lookup for fields.

* Added an example that statically imports a field from an interface.

Furthermore, fixed the test class FieldAccessInLambda.java.

* Added an example that statically imports a field from an unknown class.

* Avoid Exception in getVariableDeclaration.

* Added an example that requires super class/interface lookup for variable.

* Fixed scope checking for declared variables.

* Use EarlyTerminatingScanner instead of AbstractFilter.

* Consider all types CtVariable and fixed documentation of `createVariableAccessNoClasspath`.

* Create a more accurate CtField from super class/interface.

* Removed unused import from JDTTreeBuilderHelper.

* Added some heuristics for statically imported fields in noclasspath mode.

* Added missing EOF.

* Fixed expected and actual value in JUnit tests.

* Fixed typo.

* Replaced some spaces with tabs.

refactors the three responsibilities of equal/hashcode/signature Before:
The three responsibilities of equals/hashCode/signature were handled by the same code in SignaturePrinter,
with two major problems:
- no deep equality for package, class and method
- low performance of hashCode

Now:
The three responsibilities are handled by three different visitors:
- SignaturePrinter for signatures
- EqualVisitor for equal
- HashcodeVisitor for equal
- CtElement.getSignature is deprecated

refactors CtTypeReference CtTypeReference is where, for historical reasons, many methods where put,
breaking the initial vision and the clear responsibility. This refactoring
makes it coming back to its roots. This refactoring should neither break API
nor behavioral compatibility.

It consists of three main steps:

1) introduce CtTypeInformation which bridges information that can be both get
at compile-time and at runtime. This introduces good regularity in the API.
(This was implicit and half-done before)

2) move compile-time methods to the CtElement hierarchy (e.g.
getAllExecutables)

3) move important runtime methods in RtHelper (an old class as well)

4) remove box/unox that are only used once and are too specific for being in the interface

There still remains the problems of the hacky getPackage and getDeclaringType.
They have their counter-part in the CtElement hierarchy, but in one case they
return a reference and in the other an element. Hard to understand for the new
comer, and impossible to unify. Still, it seems we may be able to simply removing them.

Merge pull request #49 from cc18/classLoaderInEnvironment supports creation of  spoon objects on the fly for classes in class path

supports creation of  spoon objects on the fly for classes in class path with the new feature to inspect inside classes in the source class path
there was a new bug introduced: the URLClassLoader inspecting each
referenced class had two problems. firstly, a memory performance
issue: many URLClassLoaders were being created with each invocation,
but all of them using the same class path. secondly, they class loader
was closed after loading each class, but this could cause the program
to throw a NoClassDefFoundError (because the class is found, but it
can't be loaded because the loader is closed).

now, it is the Environment who gives support to load external classes
(but yet found on the source class path), providing its own ClassLoader

refactors the Spoon API. class spoon.Spoon contained a set of key static methods (e.g. createFactory(), etc.) and as such defined the Spoon API. However, being static, those methods can not be overriden. All those methods have been moved in spoon.Launcher.

spoon.Launcher is now the central spoon API, it contains:
- the command line API (main(String[] args)
- tne OO API (all public methods)
- the main logger

For instance, the Spoon maven plugin overrides createFactory

Dec 30 2013
--Christophe and Martin

Better fix for annotations in GANYMEDE. In the AST produced by eclipse's JDT compiler 3.4+ there is a type reference underneath annotation nodes that points to the type of the annotation. Spoon's TreeBuilder does not expect this, and therefore borks when it finds it, mistaking it for a value member. The fix consists of a field that says whether it just visited an annotation, and if it did, it ignores the following type reference. After exiting the type reference, the field flag is resetted. git-svn-id: file:///svnroot/spoon/trunk/spoon-core@2046 b1f50995-73fd-43b8-8ca2-fbc405a04e82
